segments.text: Okay, we're running now.
So tell me a little bit about, I see you've got some curious George dolls in the house.
Well, yes.
They don't look very, not over there for the beauty, but they are some different periods, different, many different, you know, and they look all right to you, but they're not.
Well, there are maybe one, two, three, four, five, or maybe ten or a dozen of them.
So they represent, what, different times?
Well, they are from different times, and that's what they're lying there for.
I mean, you don't have to lie in there, but I don't know where to put them.
No, but they're very nice.
Well, it's certainly something nice for me to look at and to ask a question.
Everywhere I look, I see George.
I see George there.
You sit, you sit.
George there, George there.
I saw him over there.
He's quite a part of your life, isn't he?
Oh, yes.

How has he changed over the years?
How did he change?

different people who produced it.

When you feel them, some are quite hard.

I created it after all, the character.
No, it's very hard to keep it
Halfway the way I like it.

Did you have any idea that it'd become what he did?
No, you can't have an idea of that.
You know, it comes.
It comes, it comes.
Also, at that time, what do you know, that's over 65 years ago, until we started.
We started it in Paris.
And it was quite by accident.
My husband had done some cartoons for a French periodical newspaper.
about the gilaf, the length of gilaf, you know, the giraffes use of the fire tower, or skiing, you know, nonsense.
And Gallimari, a French publisher, called us up and said, couldn't we make a children's book out of it?
They liked the scripture.
Well, we had never thought of children's books.
Well, we needed money, so we said yes.
And the first book we did was, it was a
Many years later, here, it was my brain.

Sorry about that.
Cecily?
Cecily G. And the Nine Monkeys.
So George had... Of the Nine Monkeys.
So how come you decided to take one monkey
Out of nine.
I don't know.
It was all... We get this first Curious George in France right after the Giraffe book.
You know, we thought it sort of nice.
We enjoyed it right away.
My husband, Drew, and I wrote.
It was closer to that, you know.
It was not very close to that.
It was a collaboration.
Yes.
Yes, it was a collaboration.
Except it had its disadvantages.
My husband was very slow and I was very fast.
There's nothing you can do about it that people are that way.
What came first?
The pictures or the story?
Or did the story come together?
It came together.
Sort of.
I think we often we had a, what I call a right thread through the, through the story.
You know that we wrote that first story.
And then, I really can't tell you what came first and what didn't come first.
The first book was a giraffe book?
Sure.
And was that successful?
Yes, I think so.
We wouldn't have dared it was successful, but not as enormously as George's, you know.
So then from the giraffe book, where did the idea for the monkeys come from?
Well, we just thought after the giraffe book, well, let's do another book.
And we both liked monkeys especially, all elements, but monkeys especially.
So we said, let's do a book about a monkey.
And this
We got it out of France on our bicycle street.
We left France on bicycles.
I don't know whether we have any material of us tonight.
I don't.
Do you have any here that I can take?
I think so.
That would be very helpful.
When we're done, if you want.
Okay.
Gosh, those flowers, aren't they gorgeous?
They're wonderful.
Yes.
to keep these things, yeah.
I'm a co-writer.

I have two daughters who love it, but I have 14 and 12.
Oh, they're really too big, yeah?

Yes.
Barbara and Nicole.

Barbara, B-A-R-B-A-R-A.
And her sister is Nicole.
Nicole.
Nicole.

O-L-E.

Yes.
Oh.

Makes more money.

This?

This.

Very nice.

Yes.

Yes, yes.
Oh, that's nice.
Thank you.

Some years later.

Hi.

Here.
Hello.

Lely.

Me?

Greek name.
Greek?

Greek.

Better, sir.

Yes, yes.
Cecily.

Why they like it so well?
Yeah.
Did people, did you hear from the readers that they liked this one?
Oh, sure, sure, sure.
She knows now.
I think it's 55 years now.
It's a very long time.
Sure, that's great.
And that's a lot of generations of children, too.
Absolutely, yes.
Children and grandchildren and great-grandchildren.
That's right.
And that's the mark of a classic, you know, the fact that if it goes into multiple generations, that makes it a classic.
It is a classic now, yeah.
Well, what is it that resonates, do you think, from generation to generation?
I don't know.
I think, I really don't know.
I only know that it was an immense effort for us to write them.
People always think, you know, of librarians, they say, oh, they must have had fun dashing them off.
You know, there was no effort behind it.
It took us an enormous time to do each book.
And after each book, we said, none anymore.
Too much trouble.
And then we waited five, six years, like mothers having children.
After a while, they had forgotten their paintings.
And...
Then we did another one, but we didn't space them out.
Well, what made it so difficult when people say... I don't know.
The story has to... I don't know.
It's hard to explain.
The story has to flow, and after it went this way, that my husband had ideas.
He had just his idea for, I want a monkey with a dinosaur in a museum, you know?
And I want a monkey...
Various places.
They were often not connected at all.
So my job was, more like a mother musk, you know, or whatever you want to call it, to get that story, those pictures, looking, there was a natural connection there.
And it wasn't all that way, but often.
And I don't know whether one husband there was, for instance,
I don't know whether you know the books at all.
I do.
I have them.
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.
You've read them all.
I've read them.
My children love them.
Yes.

Yes, yes, yes.
You know, now that idea came, for instance.
I finally remember that my husband, as a boy, he said, his mother said something wrong.
So we had other boys there and said, you clean the kitchen while I'm going.
Go on to the left.
And so, at that point, he did something similar.
And anyhow, that guy, they used soap powder and made a mess.
Not that big a mess, as he made, but a mess.
I don't know what it is.
I don't know.
Now, when you started, when you did the giraffes, were you working as a team then, a husband-wife team?
Oh, yes.
So you always planned to work together as an artist and a writer.
We didn't plan it.
It happened that way.
We never planned.
In a way, you know?
Yes, we did that before.
We lived in Rio de Janeiro before, and we worked together there already.
But we did other things.
My husband wrote news for the 80s.
He'd lived there for 10 years.
And he knew everybody.
And everybody loved him because he was such a cheerful fellow.
And so was I. You're fine.
You lived in Rio, and you went to France.
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.
From Rio, we went back to Europe.
My parents invited us to a related honeymoon.
But everybody left Europe, you know.
We went back to Europe.
And we stayed there a while.
We stayed four or five years with parents.
We never wanted to leave you.
Have you ever been to parents?
Yes.
Isn't it wonderful?
It's like it's not real.
It's so beautiful.
Yes, yes, yes.
It's a very magical city.
So why did you leave?
Because the Germans were right on our feet.
The evasion.
That's where we lived.
And we had nothing to go.
So my husband went in one of those large stores.
The homeowner's end, they called them before.
Department store?
Yes, department store.
And there were no bicycles left, but he found somewhere parts for bicycles.
So he made them move.
We didn't know he worked on them until we had them out.
My great surprise, I didn't know he was so efficient.
And then we started.
And we ran out south, south, like everybody else.
And then in the middle of France, we found a tray.
Yeah, I meant to say, at the back, you know what a bicycle looks like?
It has a little thing, and the back is all we could take.
Really?
So we'd take all the books we'd had.
There wasn't too many, but we had books made, which proved to be a very sensible thing to do, you know, to take the books.
Why is that?
Because they knew here what we were doing.
You know, we had to sell all of this.
Oh, so you could show... Of course, yeah, that makes sense.
It didn't really, yeah.
Yeah, that makes perfect sense.
Yeah.

Well, I tell you, we had already in Rio made, you know, investigated, wrote down all the publishers we had.
We had to start from scratch, and had a long list and so on.
And when we came here,
I came by boat at that time.
You know, I came by boat.
And my sister was on the chaise.
And she said, there's a bad letter from you, from Horton Mifflin.
Now, Horton Mifflin, there's always funny coincidences.
Horton Mifflin's juvenile editor had brought her children over here.
There's so many French women lived during this war.
She had her children here with her grandmother.
And she wrote as a letter, Grace Hogarth, I remember her name, and said, don't see anybody.
I'll come right down and sign you up.
And that's happened that way.
And actually, it was quite a disappointment for us.
We had a feeling we had to work our way up, you know.
But it also was nice.
But it was, well, as I said, we felt disappointed.
We wanted to start all over.
Do you find the children all over the world like the same things?
Absolutely.
Absolutely, yeah, yeah.
So you had no trouble taking the concept and moving it here and having it... No, no, no.
The text, nothing changed in the text.
In the picture, something changed.

The tabac, you know, the sign.
Signs in the street, one can see it.

And here, too, in one book, it looks like Fifth Avenue.
Remember that thing?
And only in that sense, anything was changed.
But the story, kids seem to laugh at the same things.
children seem to laugh, be amused by, have wonder for the same things all over the world, don't they?
Yes, it is.
We have never, we had never any complaints.
Yes, we had.

I don't know.

It's amusing.

Yes, yes, yes.
Not much.
We don't pick much.

I don't know.

Oh, yes.
Oh, yes, of course.

You get what?
Royalties.
Oh, royalties, yeah.

Constantly, yeah, yeah.

Yes, yes.

It's amazing.

Oh, he would have been a scientist.

Very hard.
To do it as well.
